# tmux-copy-cmds.shell-prompts.example — the shell-prompt-type table for the
# Alt+c command picker (tmux-copy-cmds.sh + tmux-copy-cmds.awk).
#
# Setup:
#   1. cp this file somewhere, e.g. ~/.config/tmux/shell-prompts.tsv
#   2. point TMUX_COPY_SHELL_PROMPTS at it (absolute path) where the tmux
#      SERVER can see it. display-popup runs with the server environment, so
#      an `export` in ~/.zshrc after the server started never reaches it —
#      set it in ~/.zshenv or ~/.zprofile (read before the server starts), or:
#        tmux set-environment -g TMUX_COPY_SHELL_PROMPTS ~/.config/tmux/shell-prompts.tsv
#
# Format — one prompt type per line, exactly two tab-separated fields:
#
#   <marker-ERE><TAB><num-prompt-lines-above>
#
#   marker-ERE        POSIX ERE (mawk dialect) matching a command-start line.
#                     Taken as raw bytes, never trimmed — the bash row below
#                     deliberately ends in a literal space. A literal tab
#                     cannot appear inside it (tab is the field separator);
#                     write [[:blank:]] instead. Anchor with ^ like every
#                     sane marker (also: only a marker whose FIRST byte is
#                     '#' would collide with comment syntax — ^-anchored
#                     ones never do).
#   num-prompt-lines-above
#                     how many prompt lines this prompt paints ABOVE its
#                     marker line (p10k's info line = 1; the marker line
#                     itself is not counted). Trimmed from the tail of the
#                     PREVIOUS block, which is what lets one scrollback mix
#                     local and ssh prompt styles cleanly. The fzf preview
#                     shows each block as painted on screen (lines-above +
#                     raw marker line) — the lines-above are never copied.
#
# Matching: a line matching a marker starts a command block; the text after
# the marker match is the command (a marker with only whitespace after it is
# a live/empty prompt — skipped, but it still ends the previous block). Rows
# are tried in order and the FIRST match wins, so keep more-specific markers
# first. When @copy-include-shell-prompt is 0 (the default), the strip is
# exactly the marker match plus following whitespace.
#
# Fail-fast: there is no fallback table anywhere. If TMUX_COPY_SHELL_PROMPTS
# is unset, the file is unreadable, any row is malformed (wrong field count,
# empty ERE, non-numeric num-prompt-lines-above, CRLF/BOM), there are zero
# rows, or an ERE does not compile, Alt+c aborts with a message — malformed
# rows are never silently skipped.
#
# Lines whose first character is '#' are comments; blank/whitespace-only
# lines are ignored. (The LF-only/no-BOM rule applies to every line,
# comments included.)
#
# The stock rows: local zsh+p10k (marker '❯', one info line painted above it)
# and ssh'd bash 'user@host:path$ ' (no prompt lines above). The bash path
# part is [^ ]* on purpose: the match can never extend past the real prompt
# into command text containing '$ ' — the flip side is that a cwd containing
# a space is not detected.
^❯	1
^[^ ]+@[^ ]+:[^ ]*[#$] 	0
